// As mentioned in Buffer A, we need the derivative. One can get it for free by using
// dFdx/dFdy/fwidth funcs, which is insanely useful since our "function" - iteration
// through all points and finding the two closest ones - isn't really analytically
// derivable.
//
// The problem is, derivative functions are 2x downsampled, so division results in
// artifacts. So I'm using a trick that I was recommended on the ShaderToy Discord,
// stolen from here:
//
// https://www.shadertoy.com/view/3lt3DN
// 
// Thanks a lot, Fabrice Neyret! And to Orm for the recommendation! o/

void mainImage( out vec4 O, vec2 U )
{
    float a = texture(iChannel0, U    /iResolution.xy).r,
          b = texture(iChannel0,(U+1.)/iResolution.xy).r;
    O.x = a;
    O.y = fwidth(a);
    O.z = b;
    O.w = fwidth(b);
}

